nFir# Insurance\nflttfH I, trmv&t BuiMiaf 'f$\n.\u2022mm.w\nS .V C,L\nB. a TABES\nMAX\nVL\n4$:\nMXUB\npentbto\n10 Mala atreel\n1\njr-\nr\u00bb\nDB. LOUIS P. TALLEY\nSpecialifit in X-Ray and Electro\nTherapeutics\nto Deaponeea Rospiui\nr\u00abuni I\u2014II p. a.\n^hoM Mi\nMARSHALLTOWN\ntYPOGRAPHICAL UNION\nMareHalltown, loW*! M-''*\nAek for the UNION LABEL en\nfeur printed matter, and read ntwe\nthat er* entitled to its uea.\nyhe Spirit of\n\u2022a\u00ae i92i\u00ab\nDemands Service\nWe Offer\nIncqmeTax of Course\nC. H. KEMLER\n119 Bast Main PKone 950\nESTEL\nCndeirt|^p farlon\n316 East Main St.\nNew Motor Hearse\nService*\nEOTH PHONES\n'ifc.\nSAwmk I'-ss'\nyr-\"?\niie^-\nPublished' Dally By Th\u00bb\nTIMll'J-REPUBLlCAN PRINTING CO.\nTERMS\nDally, by mall 18.00\nBy the month, by mail .60\nDally by carrier, by the menth .80\nWeekly cne ye*r by mail 1.60\nEnteral at the poatofflce at Manhalltown\nIowa, an second-class mail matter.\nMsinber of the Aasooiated Preia\nThe dissociated Press ta exclusively entitled\nto the use for republication of all news dis\npatches erodited to it or ntt otherwise cred\nited In this ptiper and also the local tiewa\npublished herein.\nAll rle.lts of\npatches herein are also xeserved.\nSome New Year.\nThe days fly past like winged things\nThe Jlres of the year burn low\nThere':* gray across the once blue\nAy,\nBlue ithadOiWs across the snow.\nThe year just done,\u2014It went so fast\nWe htid no time, it seemed,..\nFor aught but common dally tasks.\nThe rest we only dreamed.\n\"The Now Tear shall he different!\n).uite\nWe'll have more time,\" we say,.\n\"We'll do some of those things Vt\ndreamed\nEre 1.1: has passed away.\"\nThan when it wans\u2014like all the rest,'\n'Twil seem a futile apaee\nWhere!in we strove\u2014but ne'er at-\nUiined\nI\nRan\u2014but won the raoe. K.~*'\n\nBut, if those tasks that hold' ue 1ack\nFrom doinf the things we dream,\nBe all well done, with a cheerful\nsmile, /{..'I ^)ri]\nNo matter how hard they ieem,-4\nWe'U come, sometime, to a New \u00a5eaf,\nfair,\nin wlilch there'll be nothinguto rue,\nIn it wu'Il do all the things we've\nplanned\nAnd make all oiir dreams dome\ntrue.\nHazel Elizabeth iMaet^ni^Q..\n1\nIIURLEY, A WORD OF INFAMY, r&j\nJudge KenesaW Mountain JLandis\nsent tlui men to clean up Hurley,\nWisconsin in the matter of illegal\nbooze. They cleaned up. Perhapp\nJudge J-andls will be able to keep It\n'Oieane3 up.\nHurley la a syaonym for infamy. It\nis one of the-towns with mnlnheri\ntianCe. tt was Hurley where the\nstockades o\u00a3 a generation ago made\nthemselves both notorious and in\nfamous, Women were inred to that\nfrontier of vice and degredation, im\nprlsoneii in stockades. and guarded\nby armtwi brutes to be sold piecemeal\nto ot'fior brutes from the lumbef\nwods. When death finally ^oame to\ntheir relief they were buried and for\ngotten h\\ some out of the way corner.\nFinally reporters, at th^ r)sk of,\nlite, :mai\\a|re4 t^ get the story to the\noutsldf workl. Thre atockadee were\nabolishreigrted In Hhrley\nas it hm reigned since.\n\"tECiirluy f&m We -\"t!16an u'p there to\nelmiply another .evidence/tluik^ brave\nahd hpia\u00ab^ administration Of*t^e law\nla irresistible. Plague spot* exist en\ntirely tnecause decency, the majority,\npermttjf them to exist.\ntir?\ny\u201e\n.,..v v, teat \\'t\ny&rm DIIT A0AINST T0MARR0W.\n\"New Year's day isn't essentially\ndifferent from the other 365 days.\nJanuaiT 1 ia a decimal point. It is\nthe. day. when we take a ifull breath\nand st (irt again ou our annual pil\ngriraaifis of It calendar months. We\nput tti\u00abi past year behind. us, that is\nwe.think we do, and begin all over,,\nhat is we think Ware beginning all\novei1.\nA Wey Tear sermon or a New T^ar\neditorial furnishes little that. Is hew\nThere Is nothing new to say of the\nfundamentals of life. The same es\nsential needs are ours, that were the\nneeds of Adam and of Eve on that\nfirst Now year of a beginning of a\nnew ircrid. The same old Ten, Com\nmandments are in existence. They\nhave not been repealed or changed.\nThey are still law. The iSernion 'on\nthe \"Mount is still the ideal code Oif\nethics. We have managed to evade\nthose itnws, bootlegged in morals and\nethics, as It-were, but the Adam in\nhis nakedness, the oave dweller in his\nfurs a nd us, in our coats and trousers\nin ou}* automobiles or sitting above\nmodern heating plants are 'brethren\nunder our skins like thp colonel's\nlady aid Biddy O'Grady. And this\nmight be extended to cover Eve in\nher tig: leaf and Peryle and Mae in\ngeorgette waists and short skirts.\nThey're sisters too, f'\nNew Year's isn't a new game. It Is\nonly another deal in the regular\ngame 1 hat we must all sit in. Wheth\ner or not we wish We must draw\ncards. And play them. Don't forget\nthat. We must play\nThis year of 1921 will be what we\nmake it\u2014with certain limitations.\nWe can't wipe out last year or any\nother year since Adam. They are all\nin th ,s year. One thing we can't\ncharge off is the debt 1921 oweB to\nall the centuries. The fact is that we\nincline to make all our credits stick\nand drop our debts to the past. It\ncan't lie done in the processes of\nevolution the past collects its debt. It\ndistrains for them. It levies and in\nvariably finds the goods for execu\ntion. We either pay willingly or we\npay unwillingly and unwillingness\nand (svasion have tho costs to. pay.\nTbero are invariably heavy costs\nwhen i.he mortgages of tho past years\nI fall dte on foreclosure.\nTh(! point of it all is ,that our pros\nperity and our conveniences and all\nour new and -godlike cOnqueatr of\nearth and air are builded on what*\nothers have done, on dead men's\nVA,-J|^aisa,\nboneu and out of the active minds of\nthose who have Rone on leaving, not\na legacy as we are selfishly prone to\nconsider, \"but a debt. Every advance\nof last year and of all the_years is a\nmortgage on 1921.\nAt the beginning of this new year\nthe clashing demands of classes and\nclass selfishness fill the air. That fer\nment is part of the process of pro\ngress. Thsy Will, in time, balance\neach other as the entrlfugal and cen\ntripetal forces keep the universe in\nplace and hold the worlds In their\norbits. It is hard for us to see beyond\nour own particular horizons but be\nyond the blue sky line the round\nworld lies with its desires and needs\nand ambitions infinitely spread the\nsame people with the same hopes\nam\nselfishness and generosity that mark\noilr httle circle of vision. The limits\nof a tr anship and the boundaries of\na county are mere imaginary lines\nWhere once they represented a sort\nof centralisation of their own. They\ncan not live to themselves. A state\n\u00a3frn not live to itself. A nation, in this\ni\u00a3ter day when invention has crowded\nhemispheres up against each other\nand abolished seas and mountains.\nCan not live to itself.\nThe world has grown, little by little\nit has grown on the foundations pf\nthe beginning. Every day that the\nworld has lived is in the New Year\nof 1921. All the. progress in science\nand art, all the mighty progress that\npark the day is a debt. The mlght^\nliner traces back to the skin clad\nfisherman in his dugout, the rifle to\nthe club which the cave man de\nfended his home and his property and\neven the laws that permit society to\nlive were b6*ft about the blase of a\ncave man's fti^yfrom the lips of its\nmatriarch..\nSo tomorrow Isn't the beginning\nbut a renewal. There Is a long, heavy\noutstanding debt against 1921.\nThere is but one beginning. \"In the\nbeginning God created the world.\" All\nthe rest is a journey, a task, a privi*\nlege,\nMlt. FORSAN'S CLEAR RESUME.\nThe plainest, clearest and most\nunderstandable explanation of the\npresent period of business depression,\nfailing prices and low collections,\nthat has yet appeared, is given by\nJames B. Forgan, chairman of the\nboard of directors of the first Na\ntional Rank of Chicago, and is pub\nlished on this page of the T.-R. to\nday. v# ir1a r-.o\nAfter examining it reader* of the\nT.-R. will recall that each and every\nstatement made therein has from\ntime to titne been published edltorial\nly. as the opinion or prediction ,of thiSj\nnewspaper. The things that Mr. For\ngan says have happened during this\nlast yieaf are ,-^ie things tfiat the\nT.-R. said many months ago. would\nhappen and they ^ldj,\n\"On the whole,\" says Mr. Forgan,\n\"it was to be expected, but in pros\nperous. times business men rarely re\ngard the warnings of those who point\nout the weakness of the existing\nsituation, but act as it there never\ncould be a change for the worse.\"\nThat seems to be the temper of a\ngreat many business men who have\nbeen reading warnings in the T.-R.,\nand then damned the newspaper for\nconducting a \"propaganda\" for low\ner prices.^^v 7 \u2022'v'irf 'r.v:iV -Ij\nQne young mercbont of this cltft*\nhowever, Is a conspiijuous exception.\nHe manages a business with\nbranches in other cities. He read the\nT.-R/s edlt'drlals last summer, when\nother merchants were kicking, and he\ndecided to hedge. lie reduced his\nstocks of merchandise^ and when a\nprices-decline of 26 per cent struck his\nline like a bolt of lighting Out* of a\nclear sky. be had $90,000 less goodp\non hand in all of his branches than\nhe would have had had he not read\nthe T.-R. With $96,000 lee* merchan\ndise on which to mark down prices\n25 per cent, he has no complaint as\nto the editorial policy of this news-,\npaper and he stands up boldly in the\nMarshalltown Club telling his friends\nwhat happened to him.\n:f\nthem.\nAnd we are\nassured from the western camps\nwhere the sky is the limit that the\nhighest merit isn't in holding a good\nhand but in playing a poor hand well.\nTopics of the Times\nThat city of Des Moines will begin\nto feel that it belongs to Judge Wade,\nMaybe its hard times but most of\nus seem to have the money to spend\noh our pleasures.\nThe gold miners are urging a $10\nan ounce raise in the price of gold.\nThey say it costs more to produce it.\nFirst thing you know we'll be told\nthat unless we put our supply of gold\ninto the bins in Jut^e we'll have to go\nwithout or pay higher prices in Janu\nary\nMr. Kendall, who will be \"governor\nof Iowa tomorrow, says he is serious\nly considering turning the governor's\nstate agents over to the attorney\ngeneral's Office. That Is where they\nshould have been placed when they\nwere created.\nKendall is also said to be seriously\nconsidering a new appointment for\nthe adjutant general's office. If\nthere's a good officer of the 168th\nwho wants it nobody will complain\nwhen he jrets it.\nIOWA OPINION AND NOTES.\nThp Lake Parl^ News desires to\nknow \"of what good it is to pay a\nnurse to go over the county telling\nmothers that each child aught to\ndrink at least a quart of milk .per\nday, when she known and they know,\nthat nine out of ten families in the\nThe Ku-Klux Klan.\nSeveral meetings have been recent\nly held and addresses delivered fa^\nvoring revival or re-organization of\nthe famous Ku-Klux Klan, organised\nin 1867 to resist tlie reconstruction\npolicy of the republican party and\nto check racial and Sfectional legis\nlation aimed at that time against\nthe white people of the south. Ad\nvocates of the new klan claim that\nIts purposes, while directed in the\ninterest' of the whites, are legitimate\nand proper\u2014that there Is no disposi\ntion to revive the raids by masked\nraiders' of the Klan, which aroused\nso much prejudice and led to. the\nbreak-up of the organization In 1869,\nafter it had accomplished Its orig\ninal piSHi'dse.\nTIMES-REPUBLICAN, MARSHALLTOWN, IOWA, DECEMBER 31, 1920\ncounty do mighty well they get\nquart of milk per day for the averag\"\nfamily? Not only can they not get\nthat much milk but they could not\nafford to buy it it thay could get it.\"\n\"Those people who are urging a\nsinless Sunday will have to shut off\nthe electric lights Sunday night to\npi-event workmen from laboring to\nmake clectric current on the Sabbath\nday\" asserts the Sioux City Journal.\nThe Cedar Rapids Republican not\ning that there are some names that\nare dropping out of the lists of cabi\nnet possibilities\u2014among them is tho\nname OX,Frank O. l^owden. \"We had\ntaken it for granted that he would\n'be the first man named.\"\nThe Cedar Rapids Gakette explains\n\"What is a lame duck?. In business\nthe lame duck is one unable to meet\nhis obligations. In public life a lame\nduoh is a politician, defeated at the\n\u2022lection, .who, having contracted the\nhabit of feeding at the people's ex\npense doesn't like to go out and earn\nhis own living. He wants to cling\nto the governmental payroll.\"\nTo the Tipton Advertiser \"it begins\nto look as tho there Is to be a mighty\nraid on the state treasury this win\nter. We are klad we have a governor\nwho with the campaign behind him\ni^news his pledge of strict economy\nin state affairs insofar as he can\nshape legislation.\"\n\"The way to put up 'buildings is to\nput down their cost\" declares the\nMason City Globe-Gazette.\nlewd Newspapers\nBILL HAYWOOD.\nI Council Bluffs Nonpareil.]\nBill Haywood announces that he\nwin speak in a number of places in\nIowa. The American Legion post in\nDea Molhes says he will not *p\u00ab*k\nin that city if they can prevent tt.\nSome discussion will follow these\nstatements. A certain element will\ninsist that this is a free country and\nthai free speech is guaranteed by\nthe constitution.\nThis is true, but it is equally\ntrue that there is reason in all\nthings. There is abundant reason in\nthe determination of this legion post\nto prevent Haywood fromj pouring\nhis poison propaganda Into the ears\nof Iowa people.\nOurs is a government of law and\norder. It is a government of the\npeople and by the people. Haywood\nseeks tho overthrow of this govern\nment by the people. His doctrine ia\nsedition and treason. Hta propaganda\nhaa for its purpose the destruction of\nthis government and the substitution\nin its place of a government by a\nclass which he represents, the I. W.\nW-\nThe American Legion members\nfought in the world mr for this\ngovernment and for ciyttir-ation. Thev\nfought to- make the world safe fof\nrepresentative -governments. We\nhave such a government here and\nnow. They fought against tyranny\nand tyrants. And they now propose\nto still further protect this govern\nment from such tyrannous purposes\nas those which prompt Hft^wood and\nhis clan to work its destruction.\nWe. are in, favor of preserving Uie\nright of free speech to loyal citizens.\nWe are opposed to the abuse of these\nrights by feuch disloyal reprobates\nand perverts as Bill Haywood. We\nere, therefore, in hearty sympathy\nwith the announced ptu*pose of the\nloyal legionaries of Dee Moines to\nprevent the disgrace which would\nhe the portion of the capital of this\nstate if it gaVe hospitality, aid and\ncomfort\u2014and the right to abuse the\nprincipals of free speech\u2014to tt man\nwho has ir^ade himself' conspicuous\nin America by his disloyalty.\nIt Is Scarcely to be wondered at\nthat tlie very name \"Ku-Klux\"\nshould have stirred certain newspa\npers and negro arganizltlons to a\nstate of excitement. In New York\nthe National Association for the Ad\nvancement of the Colored (People has\nappealed to Governor Smith, Sfayor\nHylan ctnd others for protection\nagainst this secret society. The ap\npeal is couched in terms that loave\nno doubt, of its Intention to stir up\nsectional and racial bitterness, ft\nhas been received in the same'-spirit\nby politicians and by sensational\nnewspapers, which are rehashing old\nstories of the Ku-Klux raids of a\nhalf century ago, and telling new\natorles of race riots in Florida, Ar\nkansas and oth^r southern states\nwithout making the slightest offset\nto investigate as to their truth.\nThe new Ku-Klux movement, does\nnot appear to have met with much\nsuccess in the south. Just after tho\nwar between the states there was\nsome reason for such an organiza\ntion, to protect wWte integrity and\ncivilization. But that necessity\npassed away a generation ago. At no\ntime was there less racial (bitterness.\nThe relations of the races are being\nrightly settled. Every encouragement\nis being given the negro in educa\ntion, industry and right living. A Ku\nKlux can not assist in this work. No\n\"Grand Wizard\" of the Ku-Klux is\nneeded to preserve white supremacy\nand civilisation. Efforts to revive the\norganization, arousing the old preju\ndices, if only by the use Of the name\n\"Ku-Klux,\" will meet with discour\nagement in the south today.\u2014^Hous\nton Post.\nWhat Is a Germ?\nThe doctor's children and their\nneighbors were having a glorious\ngame of \"animal.\" The big library\ntable was surrounded by lions, bears,\nelephants, and gay gazelles. Only\nMiriam had not chosen her \"beast.\n\"Hurry up, Miriam,\" shouted the\nother children. \"Get In the game!\"\n\"Well,\" said Miriam, \"I do not\nwant to 'be a common anirtial like a\ntiser or a dog 1 guess I'll be a\ngerm.\"\n\"Aw, come off,\" said her\n\"A germ ain't no animal,\nplant.\"\n4\nhi-other.\nft LM\n[A statement to the press issued\nby James B. Forgan. Chairman of\nthe Board of Directors of the First\nNational Bank of Chicago and the\nFirst Trust and Saving* Bank.]\nTho year 1919 was still under the\nInfluence of the boom cieated by the\ngreat war, while the present year\nmarked a reaction. This reaction set\nin during: the spring and it has not\nrun its course even now and Is not\nlikely to do so for a few more\nmonths to come. On \u00abhe whole, it\nwas to be expected, but in prosper\nous ttrftes business men rarsly regard\nthe warnings of those who point out\nthe w\u00abakne\u00abM of the existing situa\ntion, Jfeut\" set an if thero never could\nbe 'a^hanxe for the worse. It is a\nweip-lttiojrn fact that vlth a rising\nmffrkifttr buying increases and 4e\ncreases with a falling market. The\nresult of all this has been that busi\nness failures, which, as I stated last\ny^ar. Had been few and unimportant\nfor some years, have increased and\nare likely to continue to increase.\nThose undertakings which owed\ntheir existence merely to the artifi\ncial stimulus of the w*r and Intrin\nsically lacked those qualities and at\ntributes necessary for sound and\nconservative progress are now pay\ning the penalty for thei\u00bb* deficiencies.\nThe failures co far have been those\nof the weaker concert)* whose ab\nsence the business world need not\nregret.\nThe immediate cause of tha decline\nIn prices which has brought on the\npresent sharp business depression\nwas undoubtedly due to the action\nof the federal reserve banks In In\ncreasing their discount rates, but it\nmust always be noted that without\nsuch action we should have had con\ntinued inflation, which unquestion\nably would have finally brought on\nnot a business depression such as\nwe are now facing and which in\nmany respects resembles the, one fol\nlowing led?, but In alt probability\nwe should have had a catastrophe\nsuch as followed the years 1J7S and\n1893. The danger at present Is due\nchiefly to the International Situation.\nEurope, It is estimated, owes this\ncountry on open book account rough\nly four billions of dollars, as a re\nsult of which farmers, manufactur\ners, Merchants, and bankers are find\ning It difficult to llquid.it# in a man*\nner \u00abtuch as ought to tAke place at\nthe present time. The demoraliza\ntion of the foreign exchange market\nwhich I not\u00ab\u00bbd la*t year is continu\ning. and there does not appear any\nImmediate proppeat of relief.\nAn important conference was\nheld In Chicago on Dec. 10 and 11 In\norder to establish a corporation with\na capital, of $100,000,000 to operate\nunder, the so-called. Edge act 'and\nthus ^14 tliv rellevjng\ntthe\nsituation.\nWhile5il}ijs conference* ^was. on the\nwhole 'a,.successful,on*. and there\nwas.JetL.no doubt that thei best opin\nion of the financial community be\nlieved that aid should be extended\nto the reet of the world in order to\nrehabilitate international trade, still\nit is.neqessary to warn against un\ndue optimism. In the first place, no\nfinancial, corporation organized In\nthis cpiintry nrlll he a panacea for\nall the evfl# now afflicting Europe\nand some other parts of the Vorld.\nTbetfe jqfcn be no complete return to\nnormal .^conditions until many of the\nmanifestation* of the social unrest\nnow existing disappear, and' the\nworld as a whole learns that the only\nfinal curp for its present ailments\nis work., Furthermore, a corporation\nwith a capital of $140,000,000 is not\nto be organised over night'. Careful\nplana must be drawn up as regards\nmany ^details, and management\nwhlfcn wfll Inspire confidence must\nbe found. Otherwise neither banks\nnor other business enterprises will\nIntrust 'their funds to such a cor\nporations It need hardly be pointed\nout that' men capable of directing an\nenterprise as huge as\n4.he\ni'\"\"\none plan\u00ad\nned ar\u00ab not easily found they are\nnot likely, to be idle at the present\ntime and among those seeking new\npositions.\nIn our own country crops of nearly\nall kind* have ftsan unusually jlarge\nand good in quality. In fact, the\ncrops hove been so large and the\nrest of the world has had such diffi\nculty In paying us for what they re\nquire of our surplus that the prices\nof agricultural products have been\nurfduly depressed and the farmers\nand cattlemen of the vountry have\nbeen complaining bitterly and' ap\npeallng to the banks for aid and as\nsistance. It la to be noted that on\n1\nREADING T*e ADV/OCATCS\nthe 0luc lava/&\nM^AfiTlLV AGA\u00bb Nit THfi\nTOBACCO haisit\nRE AD MS THE\nLAW AtVoCATSS\nTtiCY VAJ'LL PUT\na\n.Card PLAYING oki v3UWDAY\nr*gr**?\u2014\"\n\u20225'T\nSVkVEY OF THE YEAR 1920\njv\nthe whole the banks have done all\nthat could be expected of them to aid\nthis most important section of the\ncommunity, but, after r.ll. the mer\ncantile part of the industrial world\nhas had to take losse.t, and where\nthe management has t-een a safe\nand sound one proper reserves were\nset up during the prosperous years,\nout' of which the present losses are\nbeing paid. Fundamentally, the\nfarmers arc in no different position\nthan manufacturers and merchants,\nand where they have been saved\nsomething out of their large earnings\nof recent years they aro'not now in\ndifficulty. In regard to one of th\u00ab\nbranches of agricultural production,\nspecial efforts have been made to\nsave the situation. refer to the\ncattle industry. Breeders of rattle,\nespecially those of our northwest,\nhave suffered very greatly in recent\nyear* owing to lonsr continued\ndrought, so that If relief yfere not\nextended there woyld bo real danger\nthat the Herds would be depleted to\nsuch an extent that the loss might\nnever be made good, certainly not\nwithin any reasonable time. A cor\nporation was therdfors formed with\nheadquarters in Chicago which is\nnow extending credit to cattlemen\nWhere needed and deserved.\nAs last year, the demand for 'bank\ncredit has remained steady and\nstrong and discount rat\u00ab\u00ab have ruled\nhigh. As a result, banks have had\nan opportunity to make large profits,\nbut these have been somewhat off\nset by the business failures to which\nI have referred. Banks will serve\ntheir own Interest best, and that of\nthe county and of the world. If they\ncontinue to watch the situation\nelosely and wherever possible urge\ntheir customers to liquidate so that\ncredit again may become fluid and\nbe made available to serve the nec\nessary expansion of production here\nland abroad.\nThere is no reason whatsoever to\ndespair at the present time. The\nworld has received a severe shock,\nbut not one from which there can be\nno rvcovery. Fundamentally, surface\nappearances to the contrary not\nwithstanding, conditions all over the\nworld have shown progress and are\nlikely to continue to do so. The\nyear 1921 promises to be a year of\nsteady, tho possibly very slow, im\nprovement.\nChicago, December 91. 1920.\nA New Arithmetio Problem.\nArithmetic according to the aver\nage smaH hoy, was simply invented\nin order to give teachers a good ex\ncuse for punishing thelp unhappy\npupils. And, ccrtainly, little Tom\nmy Smith found it the unpleasant\nfeature of his young life,\n\"Now, Tommy Smith\" said the\nschool teacher one morning, during\nthe usual hour of' torture, \"what is\nthe half of eight?\"\n\"Whioh way, teacher?\" asked thi\nyoungster cauilou\u00bb|y.\n\"Which way 7'' replied the aston\nished lady. \"Whit do you meant\"\n'Well, on top of sideways, teacherr*\nsaid Tommy.\n\"What difference does It make?\"\n\"Why,\" Tommy explained with a\npitying air, \"half of the top of eight\nis naught, but ^HAlf of it tideways is\nthr^e.\"\nA Natural Answer.\nJones met his friend Stimson in\nthe. street the other night. 1\n\"Hallo, old fellow!\" he exclaimed.\n\"How are yoti getting on?\"\n\"Pretty well, thank you,\" answered\nStimson, \"but,\" he continued, \"I've\nsomething to say to you\u2014you'll have\nto keep your eyee open next week.\"\n\"How Is that?\" queried Jones.\n\"Because you won't be able to see\nif you don't,\" and before Jones could\nkick hlfn he was out of sight.\n'His Redeeming Feature.\nDo you mean to say\" said Wemys,\n\"that you have never discovered a\nredeeming feature in an habitual\ncriminal?\"\n\"Yes, I did once,\" admitted Briggs.\n\"Ah, I knew It I\" cried Wemys,\ntriumphantly. \"No one is all had.\nWhat was It? Love of home? Kind\nness to animals? Love of children?\"\n\"No,\" came the uncompromising\nreply \"It. was a pawnticket.\"\nSeventy thousand Sicilians await\ning an opportunity to sail for the\nUnited\nStates\nare congesting\n\"OH\n\u2022STOP To\nMYtfTLe*\nia/iul\nW\u00ab5V\n\"I1'\n1\n..^yoS^\nWho can explain why dll the\nPeople are hurrying and scurrying\nso? They act as crazy as loons, and\nthat is no exaggeration,\" said Billy\nas 